The paper deals with the problem of approximate pattern matching, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has applications in various fields such as bioinformatics and natural language processing. The paper presents algorithms for both offline and online settings, which involve computing the smallest edit distance between a pattern and substrings of a text. This problem is closely related to data structures, algorithms, and combinatorics, which are all covered by the above sub-categories. Specifically, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) are the most likely categories as they directly relate to the problem of pattern matching and its computational complexity. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is also likely as the paper deals with the running time of the algorithms. cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are less likely but still possible as they may relate to the probabilistic nature of the algorithms and their correctness guarantees.
